Golden parity fixtures verified by BOTH implementations (Go + JS) in pre-commit/CI,
one fixture family per covered hook. Never fix a parity mismatch by editing only
the fixture: decide the canonical behavior first, change the lagging
implementation, then (only if the contract itself changed) the fixture.

## Fixture family table

| Hook           | Fixture prefix     | Floor | Spawned/dispatched script         | Go mirror test                     |
|----------------|---------------------|-------|------------------------------------|-------------------------------------|
| PreToolUse     | `pre-tool-use-*`    | 4     | `scripts/hooks/pre-tool-use.js`    | `TestPreToolUse_ParityFixtures`     |
| SubagentStop   | `subagent-stop-*`   | 4     | `scripts/hooks/subagent-stop.js`   | `TestSubagentStop_ParityFixtures`   |

(Previously: `SubagentStop`'s floor was 2, covering only the valid-envelope and
malformed-envelope fixtures. The per-dispatch phase-cost recording step
(`persistPhaseCost`, REQ-hooks-001) added two required fixtures — one for the
active-change case and one for the no-active-change case — bringing the floor
to 4. See "SubagentStop phase-cost fixtures" below.)

- Go: `internal/hooks/pretooluse_test.go` and `internal/hooks/subagentstop_test.go` — byte-for-byte via `hooks.Dispatch`.
- JS: `scripts/hooks/parity-contract.test.js` — spawns the real hook process; byte-for-byte,
  except each hook's documented fail-open fixture (see below), where only stable,
  implementation-independent fields are compared exactly and any divergent message
  text is compared by shared prefix only.

## Fail-open fixtures per hook

- **PreToolUse**: the parse-error fixture, identified by its
  `permissionDecisionReason` starting with `"The safety hook could not inspect
  this tool call:"`. JSON parser error suffixes are implementation-specific
  (Go vs. V8), so only `hookEventName`/`permissionDecision` are compared
  exactly and the reason is prefix-matched.
- **SubagentStop**: `subagent-stop-malformed-envelope.json`, identified by a
  missing/malformed `json:result-envelope` fence. No implementation-specific
  message text is ever surfaced for an envelope failure (stdout is the plain
  `{"continue":true}`), so the stable `continue:true` field is asserted
  exactly.

## SubagentStop fixture workspace

The `subagent-stop-*.json` fixtures reference the literal token
`__SUBAGENT_STOP_FIXTURE_WORKSPACE__` in their `stdin.cwd` field instead of a
real path, because a static, checked-in JSON fixture cannot embed a
machine-specific absolute path. Both parity harnesses substitute that token
with the absolute path to `internal/testdata/parity/subagent-stop-workspace/`
— a checked-in, deliberately `openspec/`-free directory — immediately before
spawning/dispatching the hook. This guarantees "no active change resolvable"
so the fence-persistence step is a safe no-op and the run can never mutate a
real `state.yaml` (in particular, this very change's own state.yaml, since the
JS harness's spawned process would otherwise inherit the repo root as its
cwd). Do not add an `openspec/` directory under that fixture workspace.

## SubagentStop phase-cost fixtures

`subagent-stop-phase-cost-active-change.json` and
`subagent-stop-phase-cost-no-active-change.json` are the two required
fixtures added for the `persistPhaseCost` per-dispatch phase-cost recording
step (REQ-hooks-001). Both assert `continue:true` byte-for-byte, exactly like
the other `SubagentStop` fixtures (they are NOT fail-open fixtures); the
resulting `phase-costs.jsonl` content is never asserted here — it is a
disposable session artifact, proven instead by the unit tests in
`scripts/hooks/subagent-stop.test.js` and `internal/hooks/subagentstop_test.go`.

- **Active-change case**: `subagent-stop-phase-cost-active-change.json`
  references a second literal token, `__SUBAGENT_STOP_PHASE_COST_WORKSPACE__`,
  substituted by both harnesses with the absolute path to
  `internal/testdata/parity/subagent-stop-phase-cost-workspace/` — a
  checked-in workspace that DOES contain an `openspec/` tree, with exactly one
  active change (`openspec/changes/demo/state.yaml`, `status: active`). The
  fixture's `stdin` carries no valid `json:result-envelope` fence, so
  `persistResultEnvelope` no-ops and the tracked `state.yaml` stays
  byte-for-byte pristine; `persistPhaseCost`'s write lands in
  `.ospec/session/demo/phase-costs.jsonl`, which is git-ignored (`.gitignore`
  line 4 `.ospec/`), so repeated test runs never pollute git.
- **No-active-change case**: `subagent-stop-phase-cost-no-active-change.json`
  reuses the existing `__SUBAGENT_STOP_FIXTURE_WORKSPACE__` token (the
  openspec-free `subagent-stop-workspace/`), so `persistPhaseCost` must skip
  silently without creating `.ospec/session/` at all.
